An American-style favoritism capitalism
Do you remember the East Asian crisis? When the US Department of the Treasury and its IMF allies blamed the problems of this region on favoritism capitalism, lack of transparency, and an ineffective government?
Countries were encouraged to follow the American model, to use American accounting firms, and to introduce American entrepreneurs to teach them how to run their businesses.
No matter that under the leadership of its own entrepreneurs, East Asia has developed faster than any other region – and with greater stability – over the past three decades.
The growing Enron scandal gives new meaning to two well-known American sayings: "You reap what you sow" and "Only the perfect can criticize others."
Enron used large accounting tricks and complicated financial products (derivatives) to mislead investors about its value.
No transparency here.
It used its money to gain influence and power, shaping US energy policy and avoiding regulations.
Favoritist capitalism is not new, nor is it the preserve of any one party.
Former US Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin reportedly tried to influence the current government to intervene on Enron's behalf in the controversial conflict in India.
When he was in office, he intervened when the body defining accounting standards, supposedly independent, tried to clean up the accounting of business at the expense of senior executives.
In part thanks to him, this effort to make corporate accounting more transparent was hindered.
America's enthusiasm for bailing out airlines with billions of dollars or creating cartels to protect its steel and aluminum industries suggests that free market ideology is just a thin veil for the benefit of old companies: giving favors to those who have the right connections.
To some, the fact that Enron was not bailed out and that the problems were not revealed testifies to the absence of favoritist capitalism.
My interpretation is different: it testifies to the importance of a free press that may not stop abuses but can reduce them.
When the press began to look into Enron, the number of Congress members who had accepted money from Enron was disclosed.
Campaign contributions were not just about public interest but constituted an investment.
Like most of Enron's investments, things worked well in the short term but did not yield results in the long term.
Several lessons can be drawn from this company.
Some concerning politics: the Enron scandal reinforces arguments in favor of campaign finance reform and the need for even more effective laws that must be disclosed to the public.
Democracies are undermined by corporate interests that can actually buy elections.
However, the Bush administration refuses to disclose information that would establish the role of corporate interests in defining its energy policy.
Other lessons pertain to the economy, particularly to the economy of information.
For markets to function, for appropriate signals aimed at efficiently allocating resources to be provided, investors must receive as much information as possible.
There are inherent conflicts of interest: owners and managers are naturally motivated to present the most rosy picture possible.
The control of accounts is meant to place limits on potential abuses.
But who will guard the guards?
Who will control the account controllers?
We rely heavily on motivations.
Auditors want to maintain their reputation.
But the relationship between consulting and accounting practices brings about other distorted motivations: a motivation to please clients who do not appreciate unfavorable reports.
Arthur Levitt, the former chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, acknowledged the conflict: given that many within accounting firms focus on their own short-term interests, the integrity of controls could be compromised.
He is likely the unrecognized hero of the debacle.
But accounting firms and their corporate clients – which is not surprising, given the developing witch hunt – vigorously attacked his proposal to separate consulting and accounting activities.
What Levitt understood – and what the Enron collapse so clearly demonstrated – is that motivations matter, but unregulated markets cannot provide the best motivations on their own.
The markets cannot provide motivations for creating wealth; they can provide motivations for the types of schemes that Enron implemented.
The new economy—and its complex financial instruments—highlights the issues with reliable accounting control structures; it makes them easier to obscure.
Instead of confronting these problems, American business systematically turns away from them, supported and encouraged by American-style favoritist capitalism.
The major problem of our time is finding the right balance between government and market.
The status quo will assert that Enron was an exception: that its demise was due to fraud, that we have laws against fraud, and that those who violate these laws will face consequences and will do so.
But the vast majority of Enron's actions were legal.
Its accountants declare that its core practices complied with the law and that thousands of other companies act similarly.
They are right - and that's precisely the problem.
Investors need to be sure that the information they receive adequately reflects a company's economic situation.
In the current regulatory and legal framework, with derivatives and other off-balance-sheet liabilities, investors have no way of being offered these guarantees at present.
We need better standards and more effective laws.
Although we will never be able to prevent all abuses, we can check motivations.
We can try to instill better ethical standards.
But we cannot rely on them when so many people around the world find nothing wrong with the "revolving door" phenomenon.
They claim to manage conflicts of interest, but we see that they can manage them for their own interests.
But even when evidence of this kind of abuse becomes evident, new avenues for abuse are repeatedly created – take, for example, the American repeal of the Glass-Steagall Act, which separated commercial from investment banking.
We have repeatedly witnessed the consequences of the excesses of unregulated free markets.
We must now resist the temptation to lean towards the other extreme.
The challenge is to achieve the right balance.
